715325f-b.title: Manhattan: 124th Street (West) - St. Nicholas Avenue
715325f-b.text:
Vest 124th Street, west from St. Nicholas Avenue.
Across the view, behind the gasoline station, are
buildings on the west side of Morningside Avenue.
Those to the left, at the S. W. corner are owned
John D. Rockefeller and will be demolished accord-
ing to the New York Times article of Oct. 5, 1938.
Hancock Place runs in the line of the streetcar
tracks in the foreground. The vague structure in
the background is the International House.
1: September, 1928
2: September, 1927
George L. Balgue, photo
MAY BE REPRODUCED

715326f-a.title: Manhattan: 124th Street (West) - St. Nicholas Avenue
715326f-a.text:
W. 124th Street, east from St. Iicholas Avenue. Note the
Ninth Avenue Elevated Line running in a north and southward
direction on Eighth Avenue. The white building seen at the left
is now (1938) gone; having been replaced by a business structure.
It bears No. 280 St. Nicholas Avenue and is at the N.E. corner.
July 1929.
Geo. L. Balgue

723122f-a.title: Manhattan: St. Nicholas Avenue - 124th Street (West)
723122f-a.text:
St. Nicholas Avenue, east side, from W. 124th (right) to
125th (left margin ) Btreets, as viewed in a northeastward direction
to show a clearance at the N.E. corner of the first mentioned
point. This ia of recent occurance and included a row of 5 story
tenerents that bore No's. 280 to 285 inclusive and was similar
in construction with the 5 unit structure at the left (No's. 332
to 324 Nest 125th Street). To the right is a row of six, 3 story
dwellings (Nois. 331 to 321 W. 124th Street) that have individual
frontages of 18.8 feet and are midway between St. Nicholas and
Eighth Avenues.
